1
00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:07,120
If your chart looks like a Christmas tree or some 
form of abstract art…you might have a problem!
 
  

2
00:00:07,120 --> 00:00:12,240
That’s why in this guide, we'll strip 
away all the noise, and focus on the  

3
00:00:12,240 --> 00:00:16,400
pure essence of trading - Price Action.
 
The philosophy behind price action analysis 

4
00:00:16,400 --> 00:00:22,680
Price action trading is all about simplicity.
The core idea is that price charts already  

5
00:00:22,680 --> 00:00:28,120
reflect all the buying and selling decisions 
of market participants, so you don't need  

6
00:00:28,120 --> 00:00:34,600
fancy indicators cluttering up your charts. 
 
Everything you need to make trading decisions is  

7
00:00:34,600 --> 00:00:39,120
right there in the "naked" price action.
As a price action trader,  

8
00:00:39,120 --> 00:00:44,800
you will adopt a "less is more" approach.
 
By stripping your charts down to the core,  

9
00:00:44,800 --> 00:00:51,320
you will focus on what matters most - the only 
leading indicator there is - price itself.
  

10
00:00:51,320 --> 00:00:56,200
So what exactly is price action? 
In simple terms, it's the movement  

11
00:00:56,200 --> 00:01:01,160
of price on your chart over time.
Price action gives clues about what  

12
00:01:01,160 --> 00:01:09,304
buyers and sellers are doing. Their behavior is 
visible right there on the candlestick charts.
  

13
00:01:09,304 --> 00:01:11,680
Market structure
Let’s start with the market structure.  

14
00:01:11,680 --> 00:01:18,040
Market structure refers to the overall "map" 
of the market - the patterns of highs and lows,  

15
00:01:18,040 --> 00:01:24,440
and the price swings connecting them over time.
If you look at any price chart, you'll see the  

16
00:01:24,440 --> 00:01:30,840
market structure laid out before your eyes, the 
static record of how price moved in the past.
  

17
00:01:30,840 --> 00:01:34,840
When prices keep rising or 
falling, that creates a trend. 

18
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:41,520
In an uptrend, each new high is higher than the 
last one. We call that a break of structure. 

19
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:46,200
At the same time, each low stays 
above the previous low point. 
  

20
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:52,720
That bullish momentum continues until the 
price finally dips below a prior major low,  

21
00:01:52,720 --> 00:01:56,480
which is a change of character.
You can tell a trend is losing  

22
00:01:56,480 --> 00:02:01,880
steam when the price fails to make 
a new high after the latest rise. 

23
00:02:01,880 --> 00:02:08,920
That's a sign buyers may be losing their grip. 
 
In a downtrend, you'll see the opposite - lower  

24
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:13,600
lows and highs that can't 
quite reach the last high. 

25
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:18,200
This bearish pressure from sellers 
keeps pushing the price down. 
  

26
00:02:18,200 --> 00:02:24,160
The trend stays in place as long as 
those lower highs and lows keep coming. 

27
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:29,840
But if the price manages to top the last high, the 
trend could be reversing to bullish territory. 
  

28
00:02:31,440 --> 00:02:36,720
Sometimes, the market takes a breather 
and moves sideways between trends. 

29
00:02:36,720 --> 00:02:41,480
This happens when the highs and lows 
are roughly equal, creating a tight  

30
00:02:41,480 --> 00:02:48,440
range. We call this a consolidation period. 
 
The price stays stuck bouncing between supply  

31
00:02:48,440 --> 00:02:55,200
and demand until it finally breaks out above the 
usual highs, or below the normal lows of that  

32
00:02:55,200 --> 00:03:01,880
channel. That's when a new trend could be born.
 
For a trend to flex its muscle, it needs to  

33
00:03:01,880 --> 00:03:07,800
keep printing those new highs and lows.
But only one candle testing highs doesn't  

34
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:13,440
mean much. If you see several candles 
close above past resistance in a row,  

35
00:03:13,440 --> 00:03:19,640
that's a stronger case for buyer control. 
 
And the reverse is true for downtrends - a few  

36
00:03:19,640 --> 00:03:25,920
candles breaking below support strengthens 
the argument for seller dominance.
  

37
00:03:25,920 --> 00:03:33,320
Another thing to watch is how far each new swing 
travels. If every wave is bigger than the last,  

38
00:03:33,320 --> 00:03:38,880
this tells you the dominant force are 
gaining momentum with every cycle. 

39
00:03:38,880 --> 00:03:45,800
The growing imbalance between supply and demand 
is fueling increasingly larger price movements. 
  

40
00:03:45,800 --> 00:03:52,240
So even if the market has entered a sideways 
phase, seeing progressively larger waves suggests  

41
00:03:52,240 --> 00:03:59,920
the current bigger trend may still be healthy.
 
Speed matters too - a swift move to new highs or  

42
00:03:59,920 --> 00:04:07,320
lows over fewer candles is more powerful than 
a gradual climb or descent. It's a sign of  

43
00:04:07,320 --> 00:04:12,800
intensifying pressure driving the price.
 
One of my favorite tools is using  

44
00:04:12,800 --> 00:04:18,000
trend-based Fibonacci extensions 
to project future structure levels. 

45
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:25,200
You draw it from the lowest to highest point of a 
cycle, then to the low of the pullback in between. 

46
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:29,400
This gives you clear targets for 
where the price might stall out  

47
00:04:29,400 --> 00:04:34,600
if the trend continues as expected.
 
So while the price action might seem  

48
00:04:34,600 --> 00:04:39,800
chaotic at times, market structure 
can give you a roadmap to follow. 

49
00:04:39,800 --> 00:04:46,200
By tracking the progression of higher highs 
and lows, measuring the magnitude of each wave,  

50
00:04:46,200 --> 00:04:51,760
and noting the speed of the price movement, 
you can assess the health of the current trend. 

51
00:04:51,760 --> 00:04:57,200
Combine that with trend-based Fibonacci 
extensions, and you've got a solid foundation  

52
00:04:57,200 --> 00:05:00,520
for reading future price action.
 
Support and resistance 

53
00:05:00,520 --> 00:05:07,000
Support and resistance are the next critical 
concepts you must master. Consider them as  

54
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:13,400
price zones where the market tends to pause, 
reverse, or break through with conviction. 
  

55
00:05:13,400 --> 00:05:17,720
A support is simply a price level where 
demand is strong enough to prevent  

56
00:05:17,720 --> 00:05:22,840
the price from declining further.
When price reaches a support level,  

57
00:05:22,840 --> 00:05:29,200
buyers become more inclined to buy and sellers 
become less inclined to sell. There's a belief  

58
00:05:29,200 --> 00:05:35,440
that the price is low and likely to rise. 
 
If lots of traders subscribe to this view and  

59
00:05:35,440 --> 00:05:40,920
act on it, it becomes a self-fulfilling 
prophecy - their buying pressure causes  

60
00:05:40,920 --> 00:05:47,200
the price to bounce off the support level.
 
The inverse is true for resistance. This is  

61
00:05:47,200 --> 00:05:52,760
a price level where supply is strong enough 
to prevent the price from rising further. 

62
00:05:52,760 --> 00:05:59,240
At resistance, sellers are keen to sell and 
buyers become less interested in buying. 
  

63
00:05:59,240 --> 00:06:05,920
The general belief is that price is high and 
likely to drop, so if enough traders act on this  

64
00:06:05,920 --> 00:06:12,040
premise, their selling pressure will indeed cause 
price to fall back from the resistance level.
  

65
00:06:12,040 --> 00:06:17,360
But here's the thing - these levels are not 
set in stone. They are more like zones than  

66
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:23,240
precise prices. Picture them as rubber bands 
- they can bend, but if the market pressure  

67
00:06:23,240 --> 00:06:29,880
is strong enough, they will eventually snap.
This is where the concept of breakouts comes in.
  

68
00:06:29,880 --> 00:06:36,320
A breakout is when price bursts through a 
support or resistance with strong momentum. 

69
00:06:36,320 --> 00:06:42,480
It signals that the balance between buyers 
and sellers has shifted significantly. 
  

70
00:06:42,480 --> 00:06:48,160
If price breaks above resistance, it means 
buyers have gained the upper hand and are  

71
00:06:48,160 --> 00:06:53,560
willing to buy at even higher prices.
If it breaks below support,  

72
00:06:53,560 --> 00:06:58,960
sellers have taken control and are 
willing to sell at even lower prices.
  

73
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:03,120
The psychology around breakouts 
is simple. Before the break,  

74
00:07:03,120 --> 00:07:09,400
you often see the market testing the level 
multiple times, like it's probing for weakness. 

75
00:07:09,400 --> 00:07:15,800
Each test causes an increase of activity, 
as traders anticipate a potential break. 
  

76
00:07:15,800 --> 00:07:21,880
False breaks are common. This is where price 
pierces the level briefly, only to snap  

77
00:07:21,880 --> 00:07:29,640
back - these are known as "bull traps" above 
resistance and "bear traps" below support.
  

78
00:07:29,640 --> 00:07:34,320
But when the genuine breakout 
happens, it's usually with conviction. 

79
00:07:34,320 --> 00:07:41,160
The move can be swift and sizable, as traders 
on the wrong side rush to exit their now-losing  

80
00:07:41,160 --> 00:07:47,840
positions, while breakout traders jump in 
to establish new positions. This burst of  

81
00:07:47,840 --> 00:07:54,360
activity adds fuel to the directional move.
 
Here's a key point though - after a breakout,  

82
00:07:54,360 --> 00:07:59,240
the old resistance level can become 
the new support, and vice versa. 
  

83
00:07:59,240 --> 00:08:04,120
This is because traders who missed the 
initial breakout will often look to enter  

84
00:08:04,120 --> 00:08:09,560
on a pullback to the breakout point.
Also, traders who went short on the  

85
00:08:09,560 --> 00:08:16,880
break of resistance may look to close to their 
losing positions on a dip back to that level.
 
  

86
00:08:16,880 --> 00:08:22,080
When it comes to finding the best levels, 
there are some key things to look for. 

87
00:08:22,080 --> 00:08:29,920
First and foremost, you want to identify the 
major swing highs and swing lows on the chart. 

88
00:08:29,920 --> 00:08:36,760
These are the extreme turning points where price 
reversed after a significant move up or down. 

89
00:08:36,760 --> 00:08:42,000
Swing points are natural places to draw 
support and resistance lines because  

90
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:48,520
they represent shifts in supply and demand.
 
Not every swing point is equal. To qualify as  

91
00:08:48,520 --> 00:08:54,040
a strong level, you want to see price 
respecting that level multiple times. 

92
00:08:54,040 --> 00:08:59,520
Ideally, you'd like to see at least two 
clear rejections of the level. This could  

93
00:08:59,520 --> 00:09:05,360
be two bounces off a support level or 
two rejections of a resistance level. 

94
00:09:05,360 --> 00:09:10,560
The more times price respects the 
level, the more significant it becomes.
  

95
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:16,480
Another clue is how obvious the level is on 
the chart. If a support or resistance level  

96
00:09:16,480 --> 00:09:21,560
is really important, it should jump right 
out at you. You shouldn't have to strain  

97
00:09:21,560 --> 00:09:28,080
your eyes or use fancy indicators to see it.
The best levels are usually the ones that are so  

98
00:09:28,080 --> 00:09:34,920
clear, they almost seem to "glow" on the chart.
 
The significance of the move away from the level  

99
00:09:34,920 --> 00:09:42,120
is also key. If price just barely pokes through 
a level and then slightly reverses, that's not as  

100
00:09:42,120 --> 00:09:48,120
significant as if it rockets away from the level.
The more decisive and strong the move away from  

101
00:09:48,120 --> 00:09:54,440
the area, the more you can trust that level.
 
Here's another factor to consider - has the level  

102
00:09:54,440 --> 00:10:01,160
acted as both support AND resistance? If a level 
has been respected from both above and below,  

103
00:10:01,160 --> 00:10:08,040
that's a sign of a very significant price area. 
 
For instance, if price bounces off a level,  

104
00:10:08,040 --> 00:10:14,600
breaks above it, and then comes back to test 
it from above and bounces again, that shows  

105
00:10:14,600 --> 00:10:21,440
the level is important to market participants.
 
Recency is also important. While support and  

106
00:10:21,440 --> 00:10:26,200
resistance levels from the past can 
still be relevant, the most important  

107
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:32,080
levels are usually the most recent ones.
Levels that price has interacted with in  

108
00:10:32,080 --> 00:10:40,939
the last few days or weeks will generally be more 
significant than levels from months or years ago.
  

109
00:10:40,939 --> 00:10:42,840
Candlesticks analysis
When it comes to candlesticks,  

110
00:10:42,840 --> 00:10:48,080
most price action books will advise you 
to memorize a plethora of candlestick  

111
00:10:48,080 --> 00:10:54,640
patterns or spend hours staring at charts.
I’m gonna give you a better method to read them.
 

112
00:10:54,640 --> 00:10:59,600
First and foremost, when you open up a 
chart, take a look at the recent candles  

113
00:10:59,600 --> 00:11:03,040
and focus on their spread.
The spread is the difference  

114
00:11:03,040 --> 00:11:09,120
between a candle's opening and closing price, 
which forms the real body of the candle. 
  

115
00:11:09,120 --> 00:11:13,760
This spread reveals the market sentiment 
for that particular time period. 

116
00:11:13,760 --> 00:11:18,280
A wide spread indicates strong 
market sentiment, while a low  

117
00:11:18,280 --> 00:11:24,360
spread indicate less trading activity. 
 
Next, you look at the upper and lower wicks  

118
00:11:24,360 --> 00:11:29,680
of candlesticks, also known as shadows.
These wicks reflect the buying and  

119
00:11:29,680 --> 00:11:36,040
selling pressure in the market. Consider them as 
'rejection' areas, where the market simply didn't  

120
00:11:36,040 --> 00:11:41,200
accept the prices represented by the wick. 
 
The length of the wick, whether at the top  

121
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:45,440
or bottom of the candle, should 
always be a main point of focus. 

122
00:11:45,440 --> 00:11:52,120
It instantly reveals strength, weakness, or 
indecision in the market, and most importantly,  

123
00:11:52,120 --> 00:11:56,760
it shows you where buyers 
or sellers are stepping in.
  

124
00:11:56,760 --> 00:12:00,920
Now, considering the spread of 
the candlesticks and their wicks,  

125
00:12:00,920 --> 00:12:07,200
here are the key patterns you should focus on.
When the body of the candle takes up at least  

126
00:12:07,200 --> 00:12:11,600
half of the entire bar range, 
you're looking at a trend bar. 

127
00:12:11,600 --> 00:12:16,160
Trend bars are the heart and 
soul of market fluctuations. 

128
00:12:16,160 --> 00:12:21,600
They represent strong market sentiment 
and suggest a likely continuation in the  

129
00:12:21,600 --> 00:12:25,280
direction of the candle.
 
When you analyze a chart,  

130
00:12:25,280 --> 00:12:31,200
pay attention to instances of consecutive 
trend bars closing in the same direction. 

131
00:12:31,200 --> 00:12:37,360
If you spot several trend bars in a row, all 
pointing in the direction of the prevailing trend,  

132
00:12:37,360 --> 00:12:43,960
it's a clear sign of strength in that direction. 
 
If you notice an absence of trend bars over  

133
00:12:43,960 --> 00:12:49,240
the past ten or so candles, the 
market is likely consolidating.
 
  

134
00:12:49,240 --> 00:12:55,240
A trend-based long wick candle is characterized 
by a candle with a wick sticking out in the  

135
00:12:55,240 --> 00:13:00,480
same direction as the moving trend. The 
smaller the body and the longer the wick,  

136
00:13:00,480 --> 00:13:06,160
the better the quality of the candle. 
 
Large wicks indicate price moved a lot during  

137
00:13:06,160 --> 00:13:13,800
the candle but got rejected, signaling supply 
or demand. The upper wick acts as resistance,  

138
00:13:13,800 --> 00:13:20,320
while the lower wick acts as support.
 
In an uptrend, if a Long Wick Candle forms at a  

139
00:13:20,320 --> 00:13:27,400
key support level, it means sellers tried to push 
prices lower but failed to close with momentum,  

140
00:13:27,400 --> 00:13:33,760
causing the wick to stick out. This suggests a 
potential continuation of the previous trend. 

141
00:13:33,760 --> 00:13:38,960
The length of the wick is the first point of 
focus because it instantly shows strength,  

142
00:13:38,960 --> 00:13:45,320
weakness, and indecision in the market. 
 
The Momentum candle is characterized by a  

143
00:13:45,320 --> 00:13:52,400
larger spread compared to the previous candles, 
showing a clear directional movement in price. 

144
00:13:52,400 --> 00:13:57,520
In an uptrend, you'll notice each 
candle getting larger and larger,  

145
00:13:57,520 --> 00:14:02,740
moving a greater distance per candle. 
This shows a gain in bullish momentum. 
  

146
00:14:02,740 --> 00:14:10,480
Similarly, in a downtrend, each candle gets larger 
and larger, moving a greater distance per candle,  

147
00:14:10,480 --> 00:14:16,160
indicating a gain in bearish momentum.
When you see consecutive candles increasing  

148
00:14:16,160 --> 00:14:22,480
in size, it's a clear signal that the trend 
is gaining momentum in that direction. 
  

149
00:14:22,480 --> 00:14:28,480
In an uptrend, it means buyers are in full 
control, and there aren't enough sellers to  

150
00:14:28,480 --> 00:14:35,440
cause wide swings in the opposite direction.
In a downtrend, growing candles show sellers  

151
00:14:35,440 --> 00:14:41,360
are dominating the market, and there aren't 
enough buyers to counter their pressure.
 
 

152
00:14:41,360 --> 00:14:46,800
An Inside Bar is characterized by a bar 
that neither takes out the high nor the  

153
00:14:46,800 --> 00:14:54,840
low of its predecessor. An Inside Bar is easily 
recognizable, due to its relatively small spread. 

154
00:14:54,840 --> 00:14:59,920
The Inside Bar signifies a loss of 
momentum and uncertainty in the market.  
  

155
00:14:59,920 --> 00:15:04,400
The smaller candle suggests 
consolidation after a larger move,  

156
00:15:04,400 --> 00:15:10,920
as neither buyers nor sellers are able to push 
the price beyond the previous bar's range. 

157
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:16,360
The Inside Bar is also hinting at a 
potential breakout in either direction.  
  

158
00:15:16,360 --> 00:15:22,520
When an Inside Bar forms at a crucial spot, 
such as a major support or resistance,  

159
00:15:22,520 --> 00:15:28,040
its break can trigger quite a few 
traders in and out of position.
  

160
00:15:28,040 --> 00:15:33,080
When you see several candles in a row failing 
to break through a specific price level,  

161
00:15:33,080 --> 00:15:39,360
each forming long wicks in the same direction, 
you're looking at a multiple candle rejection. 

162
00:15:39,360 --> 00:15:46,400
In an uptrend, if multiple candles try to push 
above a resistance level but fail each time,  

163
00:15:46,400 --> 00:15:52,280
closing with long upper wicks, it's a 
clear sign of rejection at that level.  

164
00:15:52,280 --> 00:15:58,600
These wicks form a “selling pressure” zone.
 
Multiple Candle Rejections show the repeated  

165
00:15:58,600 --> 00:16:06,960
failure of price to breach a key level, suggesting 
a strong buying or selling presence at that point. 

166
00:16:06,960 --> 00:16:13,560
When buyers try to push prices higher but fail 
multiple times, it indicates that sellers are  

167
00:16:13,560 --> 00:16:19,040
stepping in aggressively to defend that 
level. The long upper wicks represent the  

168
00:16:19,040 --> 00:16:25,640
failed attempts of buyers to gain control. 
 
Similarly, when sellers try to drive prices  

169
00:16:25,640 --> 00:16:31,720
lower but encounter repeated rejection, 
it suggests strong buying interest at  

170
00:16:31,720 --> 00:16:38,520
that level. The long lower wicks signal the 
inability of sellers to close below that price. 

171
00:16:38,520 --> 00:16:44,480
These wicks form a “buying pressure” zone.
 
As price approaches a key level,  

172
00:16:44,480 --> 00:16:51,360
you'll notice the candles getting smaller in 
size. Their spread gets lower and lower. This  

173
00:16:51,360 --> 00:16:57,440
pattern of successive candles decreasing in 
size is a clear sign of Decreasing Candles. 

174
00:16:57,440 --> 00:17:04,680
Decreasing Candles indicate a loss of momentum as 
prices approach a critical point in the market. 
 
  

175
00:17:04,680 --> 00:17:10,680
The smaller candles suggest that the distance 
traveled per candle is getting shorter,  

176
00:17:10,680 --> 00:17:15,000
which is an early signal that the 
current trend is losing steam. 

177
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:20,520
For example, in an uptrend approaching 
resistance, Decreasing Candles show that  

178
00:17:20,520 --> 00:17:26,360
buyers are losing control and momentum. 
 
In a downtrend nearing support,  

179
00:17:26,360 --> 00:17:31,560
Decreasing Candles reveal that sellers 
are losing their grip on the market. 

180
00:17:31,560 --> 00:17:37,680
To increase the quality of your trade setup, 
look for Decreasing Candles that finish with  

181
00:17:37,680 --> 00:17:45,949
multiple long wick candles at the key level. This 
combination suggests a strong loss of momentum and  

182
00:17:45,949 --> 00:17:48,520
increases the likelihood of a successful trade. 
 
 
With this method, you’ll soon realize that  

183
00:17:48,520 --> 00:17:53,480
reading price action isn't about 
memorizing dozens of candlesticks. 

184
00:17:53,480 --> 00:17:57,960
It's about observing price bars as 
they form and understand what the  

185
00:17:57,960 --> 00:18:04,040
market has done and is currently doing. 
 
The context of the price move is crucial.  

186
00:18:04,040 --> 00:18:09,920
A candle can have a completely different meaning 
depending on where it appears in a price trend. 

187
00:18:09,920 --> 00:18:16,040
Is it at the beginning, middle, or end of 
a trend? Is it at a support or resistance,  

188
00:18:16,040 --> 00:18:22,120
or in the middle of a consolidation phase?
Always analyze candlesticks in the context of  

189
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:26,840
the overall price move, never in isolation!
 
Pullbacks 

190
00:18:26,840 --> 00:18:31,720
Now let’s talk a bit about pullbacks.
A pullback is a temporary price  

191
00:18:31,720 --> 00:18:38,720
movement that goes against the prevailing trend.
It's a period of price retracement or correction  

192
00:18:38,720 --> 00:18:45,200
before the trend resumes its original direction. 
 
Pullbacks occur when price moves in the opposite  

193
00:18:45,200 --> 00:18:51,640
direction of the trend for at least one bar.
The psychology behind pullbacks involves a  

194
00:18:51,640 --> 00:18:57,200
temporary shift in market sentiment. 
During an uptrend, a pullback occurs  

195
00:18:57,200 --> 00:19:03,440
when bearish pressure briefly overcomes 
bullish pressure, driving prices lower. 
  

196
00:19:03,440 --> 00:19:07,360
However, this doesn't necessarily 
indicate a trend reversal. 

197
00:19:07,360 --> 00:19:12,840
If the lower prices fail to attract enough 
selling pressure to break the previous swing low,  

198
00:19:12,840 --> 00:19:18,880
it suggests the pullback is merely a 
correction within the larger uptrend. 

199
00:19:18,880 --> 00:19:24,840
As sentiment shifts back to bullish, more 
buying enters the market, shorts will cover  

200
00:19:24,840 --> 00:19:31,960
their positions, and the uptrend will resume.
 
Not all pullbacks are created equal. We can  

201
00:19:31,960 --> 00:19:39,240
classify them into two main types based on their 
depth: shallow pullbacks and deep pullbacks.
  

202
00:19:39,240 --> 00:19:43,240
Shallow pullbacks are corrections 
that typically retrace only about  

203
00:19:43,240 --> 00:19:50,280
25% to 30% of the current leg of the trend.
They indicate that the trend is still quite  

204
00:19:50,280 --> 00:19:56,800
strong, as the countertrend moves are relatively 
minor. However, because the pullbacks are so  

205
00:19:56,800 --> 00:20:03,461
shallow, it can be tricky to time your entries 
and define your risk when trading these. 
  

206
00:20:03,461 --> 00:20:07,280
On the other hand, deep pullbacks 
are corrections that retrace roughly  

207
00:20:07,280 --> 00:20:12,760
50% or more of the current trend leg.
These are often viewed as more favorable  

208
00:20:12,760 --> 00:20:18,040
trading opportunities, as they allow you 
to get into the trend at a better price,  

209
00:20:18,040 --> 00:20:24,600
with a more attractive risk-to-reward ratio.
 
One of the main benefits of trading pullbacks  

210
00:20:24,600 --> 00:20:30,520
is the potential for higher probability entries.
When a strong price action signal occurs at a  

211
00:20:30,520 --> 00:20:36,640
key level following a pullback, it indicates 
a high likelihood of the trend continuing. 

212
00:20:36,640 --> 00:20:41,640
Confirmation is key when trading pullbacks. 
 
Look for candlestick patterns to confirm the  

213
00:20:41,640 --> 00:20:45,200
pullback is ending and the 
trend is likely to resume. 

214
00:20:45,200 --> 00:20:49,920
In an uptrend, the more subdued the bearish 
pressure during the pullback, the higher the  

215
00:20:49,920 --> 00:20:55,800
odds of a successful trend continuation.
If done correctly, trading pullbacks will  

216
00:20:55,800 --> 00:21:01,532
allow you to buy low in uptrends 
and sell high in downtrends!
  

217
00:21:01,532 --> 00:21:03,000
Breakouts and Fake Breakouts
When it comes to breakouts and  

218
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:08,280
false breakouts, you need to understand 
how to distinguish between the two. 

219
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:13,320
A true breakout can lead to a powerful 
new trend, while a false breakout can  

220
00:21:13,320 --> 00:21:20,200
trap traders on the wrong side of the market. 
 
One key thing to watch for is how price behaves  

221
00:21:20,200 --> 00:21:24,920
after breaking out of a trading range.
If it quickly reverses and comes back  

222
00:21:24,920 --> 00:21:28,520
into the range, that's a sign 
of a potential false breakout. 

223
00:21:29,240 --> 00:21:35,840
Often, these false moves are engineered by large 
institutional traders to build liquidity, before  

224
00:21:35,840 --> 00:21:41,320
driving the market in the opposite direction. 
 
To avoid getting caught in these traps,  

225
00:21:41,320 --> 00:21:46,720
it's wise to wait for a retest of the 
breakout level before entering a trade. 

226
00:21:46,720 --> 00:21:51,192
Look for price to hold outside 
the breakout level on the retest,  

227
00:21:51,192 --> 00:21:54,040
ideally with strong volume supporting the move.
In a true breakout, price should continue in the  

228
00:21:54,040 --> 00:22:02,240
breakout direction, making new highs or lows.  
 
However, if the breakout fails and price remains  

229
00:22:02,240 --> 00:22:08,680
stuck in a larger trading range, that's a sign 
that the attempted trend change has failed. 
  

230
00:22:08,680 --> 00:22:15,000
Another thing to consider is the overall market 
context. In a bull market, upward breakouts tend  

231
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:21,720
to be more reliable and profitable, while 
bear markets favor downward breakouts. 

232
00:22:21,720 --> 00:22:26,400
Trading with the prevailing trend 
will tilt the odds in your favor.
  

233
00:22:26,400 --> 00:22:31,280
Remember, the market doesn't have to 
respect the levels we draw on our charts. 

234
00:22:31,280 --> 00:22:36,454
False breakouts will occur with 
varying degrees of aggression!
  

235
00:22:36,454 --> 00:22:38,440
Chart patterns recognition
There are two main types of chart patterns  

236
00:22:38,440 --> 00:22:44,680
that every price action trader should know: 
reversal patterns and continuation patterns. 

237
00:22:44,680 --> 00:22:48,760
Reversal patterns signal that the 
current trend may be coming to an  

238
00:22:48,760 --> 00:22:54,600
end and the price could change direction. 
 
The Head and Shoulders is the most popular  

239
00:22:54,600 --> 00:23:00,920
reversal patern. It often signals that an 
uptrend is about to reverse into a downtrend. 
  

240
00:23:00,920 --> 00:23:06,760
The opposite is an Inverted Head and Shoulders 
which can form at the bottom of a downtrend,  

241
00:23:06,760 --> 00:23:12,560
hinting at a potential bullish reversal. 
 
 
Double Tops and Bottoms should be your main  

242
00:23:12,560 --> 00:23:18,560
focal point. These form when price tests 
a level twice, but can't break through,  

243
00:23:18,560 --> 00:23:23,960
suggesting the trend is losing momentum.
A Double Top often leads to a bearish  

244
00:23:23,960 --> 00:23:28,440
reversal, while a Double Bottom 
can result in a bullish reversal. 
  

245
00:23:29,440 --> 00:23:34,080
Triple Tops and Bottoms are similar, 
with the price testing a level three  

246
00:23:34,080 --> 00:23:38,640
times before reversing. 
 
 
Continuation patterns suggest  

247
00:23:38,640 --> 00:23:43,680
that the current trend is just taking 
a breather before likely resuming. 

248
00:23:43,680 --> 00:23:49,160
Flags and Pennants form quite. These 
appear as brief consolidations or  

249
00:23:49,160 --> 00:23:54,360
pullbacks against the prevailing trend.
They usually lead to the trend continuing  

250
00:23:54,360 --> 00:23:59,800
once price breaks out of the pattern 
in the direction of the prior trend.  
  

251
00:23:59,800 --> 00:24:05,880
Triangles are usually continuation patterns, with 
the trend expected to resume in the direction it  

252
00:24:05,880 --> 00:24:11,440
was going before the triangle formed. 
 
Rectangles are my favorite continuation  

253
00:24:11,440 --> 00:24:17,840
patterns. These are sideways channels where 
price bounces between support and resistance. 
  

254
00:24:17,840 --> 00:24:24,080
I like to trade false breakouts that occur 
contrary to the prevailing trend. So in an  

255
00:24:24,080 --> 00:24:30,240
uptrend, look to trade false breakouts 
below support, and in a downtrend,  

256
00:24:30,240 --> 00:24:36,040
trade false breakouts above resistance. 
 
While knowing these classic patterns is  

257
00:24:36,040 --> 00:24:40,400
important, you need to look at them 
through the lens of price action. 

258
00:24:40,400 --> 00:24:44,800
Simply memorizing patterns is not 
enough - you must understand the  

259
00:24:44,800 --> 00:24:50,760
market dynamics and psychology behind them.
This means paying close attention to market  

260
00:24:50,760 --> 00:24:57,520
structure and the key levels on the chart. 
 
Look for price zones where the market has changed  

261
00:24:57,520 --> 00:25:02,080
direction multiple times before.
If a chart pattern forms near  

262
00:25:02,080 --> 00:25:07,160
one of these key levels, it can add 
significance to the pattern's signal. 

263
00:25:07,160 --> 00:25:12,400
The overall trend is also crucial. 
Trend is your friend, as they say. 
  

264
00:25:12,400 --> 00:25:19,640
In an uptrend, bullish continuation patterns are 
more likely to succeed. In a downtrend, bearish  

265
00:25:19,640 --> 00:25:25,760
continuation patterns have a higher probability.
You always want to trade in the direction  

266
00:25:25,760 --> 00:25:31,160
of the path of least resistance.
 
When a reversal pattern forms, it's signaling  

267
00:25:31,160 --> 00:25:37,360
that the trend may be in trouble. But it's not a 
guarantee – often times, reversal patterns will  

268
00:25:37,360 --> 00:25:42,760
fail, and the prior trend will resume.
Don't jump in on the first sign of a  

269
00:25:42,760 --> 00:25:49,040
reversal - wait for price to confirm it.
 
 
During pullbacks or retracements against the main  

270
00:25:49,040 --> 00:25:56,200
trend, continuation patterns can offer low-risk 
entries if you expect the trend to resume.  
  

271
00:25:56,200 --> 00:26:02,440
Again, look for fakeouts, against the current 
trend - when a pattern breakout fails and price  

272
00:26:02,440 --> 00:26:09,040
quickly reverses. These are good opportunities 
to enter, capitalizing on trapped traders,  

273
00:26:09,040 --> 00:26:14,880
how thought the trend was about to change.
 
No two patterns are exactly alike in the real  

274
00:26:14,880 --> 00:26:21,440
world. As you analyze more and more charts, you'll 
develop a keener eye for the subtleties that  

275
00:26:21,440 --> 00:26:27,000
separate successful patterns from failures.
You'll start to recognize how certain  

276
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:32,880
patterns tend to play out in specific 
markets, timeframes, or conditions.
  

277
00:26:32,880 --> 00:26:38,760
Of course, no pattern is guaranteed. Approach 
patterns with the combination of respect and  

278
00:26:38,760 --> 00:26:41,640
skepticism they deserve!
 
Volume Price Analysis 

279
00:26:41,640 --> 00:26:46,400
Price Action becomes 10 times more 
effective with the help of volume. 

280
00:26:46,400 --> 00:26:51,480
Volume is the lifeblood of the markets. 
It reflects the actual buying and selling  

281
00:26:51,480 --> 00:26:55,680
pressure behind every price move. 
 
When you're looking at a chart,  

282
00:26:55,680 --> 00:27:02,240
the price bars show you what's happening, but 
the volume bars reveal why it's happening. 

283
00:27:02,240 --> 00:27:08,520
Volume tells you about the intensity, urgency 
and commitment behind the price action. 
  

284
00:27:08,520 --> 00:27:14,280
Here's how you can use volume to confirm or 
question what you're seeing in the price: 

285
00:27:14,280 --> 00:27:18,280
First, look for convergence 
between volume and price. 

286
00:27:18,280 --> 00:27:25,080
In an uptrend, rising prices should be accompanied 
by rising volume. This shows genuine buying  

287
00:27:25,080 --> 00:27:30,440
interest that can sustain the move. 
 
In a downtrend, falling prices with  

288
00:27:30,440 --> 00:27:36,560
increasing volume signal strong selling 
pressure that could drive prices lower. 
  

289
00:27:36,560 --> 00:27:42,360
Be wary of divergences. If prices 
are rising but volume is falling,  

290
00:27:42,360 --> 00:27:48,960
it's a warning sign. The uptrend may be 
losing steam. Buyers are less committed.

291
00:27:48,960 --> 00:27:56,360
An upside breakout on low volume is suspect. 
 
 
Likewise, if prices are falling but volume is  

292
00:27:56,360 --> 00:28:03,280
drying up, sellers may be losing control. 
The downtrend could be nearing exhaustion. 
 
  

293
00:28:03,280 --> 00:28:08,800
Look for volume spikes near support and 
resistance. Major players often show  

294
00:28:08,800 --> 00:28:16,000
their hand at key levels. If there's a volume 
surge as price tests a support level and holds,  

295
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:23,400
that's often a sign of strong demand absorbing the 
selling pressure. The support is likely to hold. 
  

296
00:28:23,400 --> 00:28:27,680
Also, track volume during 
breakouts. A valid breakout,  

297
00:28:27,680 --> 00:28:34,720
up or down, should occur with an expansion 
in volume. This confirms the price action. 

298
00:28:34,720 --> 00:28:42,040
But a breakout on low volume is more likely to 
fail, trapping traders in the wrong direction. 
 
  

299
00:28:42,040 --> 00:28:48,800
Also watch for climactic volume. After a strong 
run-up, a huge volume spike with a wide-range  

300
00:28:48,800 --> 00:28:55,760
price bar can signal buying exhaustion - a 
"buying climax." Supply may be taking over.  

301
00:28:55,760 --> 00:29:03,720
The uptrend is in jeopardy. The reverse is true 
for a selling climax after an extended decline. 
  

302
00:29:03,720 --> 00:29:11,000
Monitor the volume patterns in consolidations. 
Is volume contracting as the price range narrows?  

303
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:17,240
This can be a sign of decreasing volatility 
and building pressure for the next move. 
  

304
00:29:17,840 --> 00:29:23,560
Look for high-volume reversal bars. A 
wide-range bar on massive volume that  

305
00:29:23,560 --> 00:29:29,320
reverses an existing trend is a red 
flag. For example, a bearish momentum  

306
00:29:29,320 --> 00:29:36,200
bar with huge volume after an uptrend is 
a sign that sellers have taken control. 
  

307
00:29:36,200 --> 00:29:42,280
Think of volume as the fuel and price as 
the vehicle. A rally or decline can only  

308
00:29:42,280 --> 00:29:47,080
go as far as the fuel in the tank.
As a price action trader, you always  

309
00:29:47,080 --> 00:29:53,180
want to be on the stronger side of the market - 
the side with more aggressive volume behind it.

310
00:29:53,180 --> 00:29:56,800
And, if you want to really take 
your trading to the next level,  

311
00:29:56,800 --> 00:30:08,160
make sure to check out these next videos.

